@bmitc I'm not sure how I could be clearer than I was in https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/30701#issuecomment-1127871137 but we're actively working on it, and we absolutely intend to finish implementing it.

I agree that engineering something to handle multiple windows from the beginning isn't especially challenging as a concept (although this is an application framework, and not a window manager: two very different things). What makes it complicated is the legacy of APIs that we need to continue to support without breaking them (when possible: there will be some breakage required where concepts crash into each other).

Also, as you guessed, Flutter started as a mobile-only framework, and our roots are showing here: multiple windows wasn't engineered in from the beginning because at the time we were focused exclusively on mobile, and as a small team we had plenty to do to just finish it for the one platform. Retrofitting the concept many years later onto seven different platforms is naturally complicated and involved, and we also want to do it correctly, so we're being careful.

@FlafyDev Thank you for the design document. That will be helpful to read.

@hlwhl Thank you for the link to the multi-window tasks. That is definitely something I was looking for. This particular issue is not marked as in progress, so that is helpful to be posted here.

@gspencergoog Thank you for the response. I had read that comment, but I was looking for something more than "we're working on it". It's a long-standing issue, so that type of response unfortunately doesn't hold very strongly when just reading it, although it does seem clear now that you mean it! 🙂 The same issue actually holds in .NET MAUI and Xamarin Forms before that, with similar responses and similar years of waiting. However, your elaboration here does help as do the other links that were provided. I do wish it was considered from the beginning, but I'm sure the team is now wishing that too. 🙂

I'm sure the concern can be understood for desktop developers wanting to develop desktop applications with Flutter. There is already built-in concern of a cross-platform app framework being spread too thin across effectively thinly overlapping targets (mobile, web, and desktop and others), and so there's a lot of hesitation when there isn't visible progress on a primary desktop feature.

Thank you again for the links and reiteration!
